{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The conversation history passed to the LLM is trimmed to the most recent 10 messages when the full history exceeds the context window.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Failure boundary is local list/windowing logic: selecting the newest 10 items before request assembly. MOCK-MISS check: this behavior can fail inside one function (off-by-one/order) without any module handoff failure. REAL-INFRA/LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP do not apply. Rejection gate: considered Integration, but behavior text is a pure transformation rule ('trimmed to the most recent 10 messages') with no required cross-component interaction evidence.","test_description":"Call the history-trimming function with histories of size 9, 10, 11, and much larger; assert output length is <=10, preserves recency order, and exactly matches the latest 10 messages.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.74,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The generated response addresses the customer's question rather than producing a generic or off-topic reply.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on real model output quality (relevance vs generic/off-topic), which a stub cannot validate. MOCK-HIDE: deterministic canned responses would always pass rubric checks and miss true relevance failures. Rejection gate: considered Workflow, but behavior text asks for single-response quality, not correctness across multiple agentic handoffs.","test_description":"Run a curated set of real customer questions against the production prompt/model; score each response for question relevance/off-topic rate using human-labeled or rubric-based evaluation and fail when relevance drops below threshold.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.82,"Workflow":0.08}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The tone re-check correctly identifies when a response is too formal for a casual-tier customer and triggers regeneration.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior requires model judgment about tone appropriateness ('too formal for a casual-tier customer'). LLM-DEP applies: the classification/flagging decision can vary and must be validated with a real model. Rejection gate: considered Workflow, but this behavior only requires one critical model decision plus trigger ('identifies ... and triggers regeneration'), not validating the full downstream multi-step outcome quality.","test_description":"Use real tone-check path with a dataset of intentionally formal candidate replies for casual-tier users; verify flagging accuracy and that regeneration is invoked when flagged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.21}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full exchange (user message, generated response, any regenerations) is persisted to the database with correct timestamps.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Persistence correctness here depends on real DB write/read behavior and timestamp materialization across actual storage boundaries. MOCK-HIDE: mocked repositories can miss schema/default timestamp, precision, timezone, transaction, and ordering issues that appear only with real DB I/O. Rejection gate: considered Integration, but behavior text requires real persistence semantics ('persisted to the database with correct timestamps') and does not provide disqualifying evidence that in-process fakes are sufficient.","test_description":"Execute the chatbot flow against a real test database, including a regeneration case; query stored records and assert all exchange entries exist, timestamps are present/valid/ordered, and regeneration records are linked correctly.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.24,"System":0.68,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the tone check triggers regeneration, the second response replaces the first — the customer never sees the rejected draft.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This is a sequenced agent pipeline property: initial generation -> tone decision -> regeneration -> final response exposure. MULTI-STEP applies because correctness is about cross-step handoff and final visibility guarantees, not one step in isolation. MOCK-HIDE: simplifying to one stubbed step can miss race/state bugs where rejected drafts leak to user output.","test_description":"Run end-to-end conversations through the real tone-check/regeneration pipeline; for cases where tone check fires, assert user-visible output equals regenerated response only, while rejected draft is retained only in internal logs/audit storage.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.24,"Workflow":0.61}}]}
